<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-567  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 567.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Sept 10 1990 v7 n35 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Letters. (letter to the editor)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shnier, Mitchell.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>LETTERSandM;THEORY VS.andP;  FACTandM;Bill Hancock's column &quot;Which twisted pair is in your future?&quot; contains arather ambiguous description of what is balanced about twisted pair, and whathappens at higher frequencies.andP;  (See July 9 issue, page 23.)andM;Balanced means that the resistance and impedance (of each of the wires of atwisted pair) to ground is equal.andP;  Therefore, both wires will be affectedequally by outside electrical noise, and this outside noise will then becancelled out at the receiver.andM;The information on the twisted pair is a differential signed (the signal isthe difference in voltage between the two wires).andP;  The receiver doesn't seeany signal that is common (such as both wires getting exactly a 1-voltspike).andM;The column says that &quot;the theory of balanced energy is not achieved&quot; athigher frequencies.andP;  The theory works just fine at higher frequencies: Theproblem is that at higher frequencies the characteristic impedance becomesmore important, and at the same time, ti becomes more sensitive to smallvariations in the geometry and construction of the cable.andM;Therefore, &quot;telephone-quality&quot; twisted pair may not be suitable formultimegabit-per-second data transfer because its construction is notconsistent enough, and variations in the impedance will cause reflections(echoes).andM;Just as it is difficult to understand someone in a room with an echo, so itis impossible for a data receiver to receive the data reliably.andP;  MitchellShnier Professional Engineer Integrated Intelligence Toronto, OntarioandM;Mr.andP;  Shnier is quite correct is pointing out that the theory of balancedenergy works fine at higher frequencies.andP;  However, he also points out that,because of other variances, telephone twisted pair may be unsuitable athigher frequencies--which was the point of the column.andP;  In theory, balanceshould be achieved.andP;  But work at IBM and other companies with much moreexperience in electrical transmission theory than myself has yielded researchthat backs up my statement that balanced energy has not yet been achieved inpractice.andO;</TEXT></DOC>